<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="c515b7a6c1c6143f06a503f2f261924c" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Big, Red Beatstick!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13760'>John "Nobody Home" Doe</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13760&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 6, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well, the text spoiler for ROTK has finally come out. To commemorate the occasion, I think a cultural break-down is in order. (Note: I started this article a few days ago . . . . It was a long time in production!)  Being a fan of Sauron culture, I couldn’t resist the opportunity to sound off on one of the heretofore, most downtrodden of shadow cultures: the red hordes of the big guy himself!<br />
	Of course, it’s only been a few days since the spoiler came out.  Since few people have had a chance to really play-test the new cards (myself included), most analysis will be purely speculative at this point.  Just go on the Decipher ROTK message board if you want proof of how incoherent and senseless the general discussion of ROTK is right now.<br />
	I guess what I’m trying to say in short, is that this article is going to have a lot of mistakes. Time will undoubtedly prove me wrong on several points, and cards that everyone thought would make good Frisbees, will eventually be the foundation of many competitive decks.  So be kind to me. Remember, even the obvious needs to be said so we can all move beyond it.<br />
<br />
Note: my analysis is focusing on the meta at BIG tournaments like PSQs and the Conventions. I don’t really care if Twilight Nazgul corruption is huge at your local card shop meta. It’s not big at the major-leagues. Get over it.<br />
<br />
	OK, let’s get down to business. First I’ll talk about the new Sauron culture overall.  My focus will be on open format unless otherwise noted.  After a few observations, we’ll do a card-by-card analysis.<br />
<br />
	First thing I noted when looking through the list, is that a few old-school Sauron strategies may have fallen by the wayside:<br />
<br />
Take Sauron Corruption/Burdening decks.  All we get in this set is Orc Officer and Gorgoroth Attacker. The Attacker is worthless since he requires site control which just takes up too many cards. While the Officer is a good fit in the old Overwhelming/ Burdening decks (the ones that use Enduring Evil big-time), he’s the only useful burdening card in the Sauron culture.<br />
<br />
At first glance, it looks like the old Sauron discard strategy didn’t get much help either.  Nothing here is going to help you deck your opponent quickly. However the discard fans out there shouldn’t get too discouraged.  One of the major weaknesses of the old discard strategy was that even once you decked your opponent at site 6, the minions still couldn’t fight their way out of a paper bag.<br />
This may have changed with ROTK. Discard fans should take a real close look at the new Initiative mechanic.  Now you can include cards that benefit from all that discarding you’re doing!  Discarding decks may finally have a viable fighting element.  At the very least, everyone should be taking a new look at Desperate Defense of the Ring (just read the text and it should be obvious).<br />
<br />
Oddly enough, it looks like Decipher decided to leave the Sauron swarm behind in Tower block.  But they included 4 new trackers and a bunch of cycling ability you say?  True, but if you look at those trackers, they aren’t really swarm minions, but are really meant to fit an overwhelming strategy while helping to make your orcs more affordable.  Only Orc Seeker really fits the swarm mold.  More on this later.<br />
As far as the cycling options, you’ll notice very few of these help you DRAW more cards (vital to any sort of swarm).  They’re all geared towards discarding unwanted cards.  This is good news for Sauron fans since a big weakness of several deck-types was that Sauron couldn’t cycle at all (many decks had to be the minimum of 60 cards just to function).  I wager that’s about to change.  I wouldn’t be surprised to see some of the old 30-card overwhelming shadows going to 40 cards.<br />
Sauron’s Hatred and Fires Raged Unchecked are worth a look from swarm fans, but that’s about it.<br />
<br />
So what are the new forces of Sauron good at?  The big cultural weaknesses of the old Sauron were, that none of them were naturally fierce or damage +1, and they all kept roaming for most of the game.  While they were all pretty big for their cost and had lots of vitality, that didn’t help much when they could only cause 1 wound per skirmish phase.<br />
Beseigers have alleviated the roaming problem somewhat.  As far as the lack of damage bonuses . . . . Threats might just be the solution.  Of course, it’s impossible to say much about Threats until we’ve seen them in action. But here’s hoping . . . .<br />
<br />
Of course, the tie-in between Threats and the old Hate decks should be obvious.  Nuff said! Let’s take a look at the cards. We’ll start with the minions, moving from most to least expensive.<br />
<br />
I thought I’d start with the old fashioned site 6 orcs and save Beseigers for later.<br />
<br />
Host of Udun.  10-21-5-6 (that’s cost-strength-vitality-site #). He removes Threats to make himself cheaper.<br />
Toss in a few pumps and he’s a good candidate for overwhelming someone (and he might do it without any help). He’s too expensive to use in the cost-heavy Sauron strategy. But what about his ability? <br />
Well, realize that since Threats can’t go above the number of companions, there won’t usually be more than 5 threats available (Thanks Enquea!). That puts him at 5 cost (7 cost usually w/roaming), but you might want to use those Threats for something else. And how hard is it to accumulate Threats? Until that question is answered, I’d leave this guy in the storage box.<br />
Verdict, until we don’t care about blowing 5 Threats, he’s scrub-bait.<br />
<br />
Army of Udun. 9-19-5-6. Plays around with Threats for marginal strength boosts.<br />
<br />
11 is just too much to pay for a guy whose only ability is to go str +1 (like we care about 1 more when he’s already 19).  You can use your threats better than that. His regroup ability is just silly. Like I’m going to go to all the trouble of getting this guy into play and then discarding him for a measly Threat. Double-move? Thank-you, don’t mind if I do. Host is better than this guy.<br />
<br />
Orc Archer Troop. 6-15-4-6. An archer who shoots again when you have initiative and goes fierce!<br />
Nice! He’s pretty much always damage +1 which puts him on par with Uruks. He’s big enough to win easily. And if you have initiative, he’s money. If you’re thinking of adding an initiative element to your deck, this guy is a must-have. Combo him with Desperate Defense of the Ring and Enduring Evil. Thumbs up! Best big minion I’ve seen yet.<br />
<br />
Mordor Savage. 4-10-2-6. Exert + another [S] orc = Threat.<br />
<br />
Good stats. This is a common theme in Sauron culture. To offset the high site #, they get above average stats for the cost. 4 cost in most cultures would net you a 9 strength, 2 vitality minion.<br />
That aside, if you want to add Threats, this guy is an easy way to do it. If Greenleaf decides to peg him one, so what? All it means is the wound got transferred directly to Greenleaf instead of having to go through the Threat mechanic. A wound is a wound, however it got there.<br />
<br />
Orc Assault Band. 4-10-3-6. Exert to make another orc strength +6 IF you spot 6 companions.<br />
<br />
Let’s face it. You don’t see 6 companions that often anymore. Nice large fellowship deterrent, but Enquea’s already got the market cornered. Next!<br />
<br />
Orc Marauder. 4-11-3-6. Spot 3 other [S] orcs to send him strength +5.<br />
<br />
Not really a bad ability. But the problem is getting him out with 3 other orcs. In a big minion beat-down strategy that really isn’t too likely (until site 8 or 9). Might be fun to summon him at site 9 with Above the Battlement or something. Might work nice in a Beseiger strategy where you can engineer having the right number of minions out. We’ll see.<br />
<br />
Orc Savage. 3-9-3-6. Nice stats. Still looking for 6 companions to work.<br />
<br />
But the payoff is even better than the Assault Band. Strength +9?! This is really tempting for the price (and he’s got typical Mordor super-stats). Another thought occurred to me: with the new Threat mechanic, people might be a little reluctant to kill off companions just to keep below Enquea’s radar. If that turns out to be the case this guy is a cheap way to cause a real dilemma for your opponent.<br />
Verdict: He might just be really good.<br />
<br />
Orc Rager. 3-9-3-6. Ditch him to make another [S] orc strength +4.<br />
<br />
I like options in the skirmish phase. This guy gives you options in the skirmish phase. Real simple text. I like him.<br />
<br />
Orc Officer. 3-9-3-6. Slaps on burdens when you overwhelm someone.<br />
<br />
Now, I acknowledge that Sauron is pretty good at orchestrating the overwhelm. But I’ve always been suspicious of cards that trigger off of the death of a FP character.  He’s worth a try in a Burdening/Overwhelm deck with Enduring Evil, but my guess is that he’ll turn out to be too situational to rely on.<br />
<br />
Orc Destroyer. 3-9-3-6. Spot 3 orcs and remove some twilight to draw a card.<br />
<br />
“At that close range we won’t last long against those Orc Destroyers!” Sorry . . . OK, looks like he’s geared to support the swarm. Problem: Sauron has enough problems getting enough twilight without blowing it on card drawing. Sauron already has plenty of card drawing options from Tower block and before without including a mechanic that needs twilight to work. Thumbs down. He really is an “Orc Destroyer.” Destroys your chances of playing more orcs!<br />
<br />
Mordor Warrior. 3-9-3-6. Spot 3 orcs and discard a card, and you can make a comp. strength -3.<br />
<br />
This doesn’t seem a likely candidate for the overwhelm strategy since spotting lots of minions isn’t its strong suit. The swarm? Nah, I’d rather have a way to get more minions. Still, I’m not entirely certain that the new overwhelm strategy is going to have as tough a time getting out 3 minions as its Fellowship block predecessor. Jury is still out on this one.<br />
<br />
Mordor Veteran. 3-9-3-6. Remove 3 threats to send an orc through the roof.<br />
<br />
If that +8 is going to nab you an overwhelm, those are probably threats well used. Other-wise, just leave them to do their normal thing. Again, this guy means options. I love versatile minions. I’m excited about this guy.<br />
<br />
Mordor Regular. 3-8-2-6. Exert + spot another orc = 1 Threat.<br />
<br />
Same as Mordor Savage (see above). But he’s cheaper. Cheaper Threats are better Threats. I’d say he’s a better utility minion than the Savage.<br />
<br />
Mordor Guard. 3-9-3-6. Exert 3 [S] orcs to add 3 Threats (Nice), then take them all away in the Regroup (Say What?!).<br />
<br />
I’ll pass. I’d like my Threats to stick around thanks. Yeah, I’m sure there’s all sort of neat things you can do with those threats while their out. But complex mechanics are usually bad mechanics. Someone may manage a nasty combo with the Ringwraith condition Put Forth His Strength, but we’re talking about Sauron today. Likelihood is that you won’t even manage to break even with this guy. Thumbs down!<br />
<br />
Mordor Assassin. 3-9-3-6. Assigns to Ring-bearer when someone gets overwhelmed.<br />
<br />
(See Orc Officer above. The same commentary pretty much applies). Might be OK.<br />
<br />
Mordor Defender. 2-7-2-6. Same as the Regular and Savage, only cheaper (which is better).<br />
<br />
Don’t expect these stats to win skirmishes for you without lots of help. The main thing you want from these lower costed orcs is their text abilities.<br />
<br />
Mordor Fighter. 2-7-2-6. Spot a Threat and another orc to get the initiative.<br />
<br />
If your deck really wants the initiative, it might pay to pack a couple of these guys to back-up the multiple copies of Some Secret Art of Flame in your deck. Good utility minion.<br />
<br />
Mordor Trooper. 2-6-2-6. Remove 2 Threats to make a [S] orc strength +6.<br />
<br />
Not as over-the-top as the Veteran, but he is cheaper and +6 isn’t bad at all. Best played in conjunction with a bigger minion for overwhelm potential. Multiple Troopers and Veterans is a must-have for any overwhelm deck.<br />
<br />
Orc Brood. 2-7-2-6. Discard 3 cards from hand to make him strength +3.<br />
<br />
Nice, simple way of clearing a clogged hand. Not much else to say about it. While a few boosts will guarantee he wins, he’s a long way from overwhelming potential, at least against fighting companions (and they’re the ones who matter). Compare him with other anti-hand-clog options out there to see if he’s right for you.<br />
<br />
Orc Butcher. 2-6-2-6. For each [S] condition, he’s strength +1.<br />
<br />
Bringing back the old classic. Sauron decks have always been condition-heavy. It doesn’t look like that’s going to change in ROTK. A cheap minion who gets quite big very quickly. Always worth considering if you have the room for him.<br />
<br />
Orc Fanatic. 2-7-2-6. Discard him to make another [S] orc strength +3.<br />
<br />
Strength +3 isn’t necessarily a good trade-off for losing that extra minion on the table in the regroup phase. However, you never know when that extra boost won’t prove crucial.  Like the Rager, this guy gives you options (just not-as-good options) and is worth considering.<br />
<br />
Mordor Soldier. 1-3-2-6. Remove a Threat to make him strength +4.<br />
<br />
Strength +4 doesn’t seem like much when you consider that it only makes him a strength 7. But note that you can do this multiple times. -3 Threats puts this guy at a strength of 15. For 1 or 3 twilight, that doesn’t seem too bad. Besides, Sauron is so expensive that some low-costed support is always welcome.<br />
<br />
That’s it for our “standard” orcs. I held off including the Trackers so I could lump them all together. All the Trackers have the ability to make the site # of each [S] orc -1.<br />
<br />
Orc Seeker. 4-11-3-6. Tracker. If you’ve got the initiative when you play him, spot another [S] orc to draw 2 cards.<br />
<br />
Great stats. If you’re thinking of combining your old swarm with Initiative, then this guy is a good fit. If not, he’s too expensive to justify including. Use the empty slot for other 4 cost Trackers like Grishnak or Orc Patrol.<br />
<br />
Orc Stalker. 3-8-2-6. Tracker. If you have the Initiative, this guy is a strength +8.<br />
<br />
Reduces everyone’s cost and gets huge! Great minion. But I wouldn’t use him in a swarm necessarily, since card drawing is more important than strength boosts in the swarm. I think multiples of the Stalker, Chaser and Pursuer could form the foundation of a deck that uses only cheap minions and then focuses on making sure they become very large (have to see how it pans out in play-testing . . . .).<br />
<br />
Orc Chaser. 2-6-2-6. Tracker. Initiative = strength +6.<br />
<br />
See Orc Stalker.<br />
<br />
Orc Pursuer. 1-5-2-6. Tracker. Initiative = strength +5.<br />
<br />
See Orc Stalker. But note that you’re getting out of overwhelm range now (except for those elusive hobbits). But I admit that it’s hard to resist the prospect of getting a 10 strength minion out for the cost of 1 twilight. Besides, 1 cost for a minion that makes everyone else cheaper is not bad at all.<br />
<br />
Now, let’s move on to the Beseigers. Look everybody! It’s the site control Uruks again! And I’ve got this sneaky suspicion that Decipher didn’t learn a darn thing from that failed experiment.<br />
My overall impression of these guys is this:<br />
1-It’s easy enough to stack orcs and play them again. So far, so good.<br />
2-They’ve got good stats for the cost and their text abilities are pretty neat. And they stop roaming a site 5 (that alone might be a good argument for playing them).<br />
3-Controlling sites looks iffy though. You’ve got 3 cards that do it for you: Din of Arms, Tower Walkway, and Troop Tower. Din of Arms is just weird. While the other two might be able to do it for you . . . . I don’t know, we’ll see.<br />
I know Uruk site control has prejudiced us towards this kind of deck, but I’m willing to give them a chance. After all, Dunland site control was actually quite a success (remember Vegas!). Of course, any good Dunland player knows that Dunland must go first in order to control sites immediately. They knew this because once the fellowship got set up, their minions would have a tough time stacking. Furthermore, site control takes time to set up, so you have to start early. Besiegers roam longer than Dunland and their conditions need to be out to work the magic. I’m not sure they can get going early enough to work.<br />
Anyway, here goes:<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Troop. 6-14-4-5. Stack a besieger and make this guy strength +2.<br />
<br />
As far as I know (and that’s not very far) you can perform this ability multiple times. Could help him overwhelm someone. Not bad.<br />
Note on all these big Sauron minions: Normally I’d be really suspicious of playing big, high-cost stuff for fear it would clog my hand. I’m not so worried about that anymore because of all the discarding methods available. If these guys come out at site 2, there’s plenty of ways to throw them to the discard pile.<br />
<br />
Siege Commander. 5-12-3-5. Discard 2 cards from hand to make a Besieger fierce.<br />
<br />
See that note about big minions above? Very nice. At 12 strength, he’s a great candidate to go fierce himself. Solves the age old problem of Sauron: “how do I cause more wounds than the one I caused in that single skirmish?” Thumbs up!<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Officer. 5-12-2-5. Discard 2 cards to play a stacked, fierce and strength +6 Sauron minion in the skirmish phase.<br />
<br />
If you can get some orcs stacked, this guy is bad news. Just about any Sauron minion’s stats are going to hurt with a +6 boost. Of course, twilight costs are going to ensure we don’t see too much of this until site 8 or 9. I really think the stacking thing is going to be hurt by how costly Sauron is to play.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Pillager. 4-10-2-5. While he’s stacked, all besiegers are fierce.<br />
<br />
Not bad. It’ll really hurt if you can pull it off. Just remember that high cost (for roaming) and the combo-reliant nature of site control means that you won’t get much use from these guys until late in the game. Wouldn’t you rather be doing things before site 5 too? Thought so. Don’t count on these guys too much.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Ransacker. 4-10-2-5. If he’s stacked, you can discard him to make a [S] orc strength +5 (or +10 if you have the initiative).<br />
<br />
Well, toss Some Secret Art of Flame into the mix with your site control stuff, and there might be some possibilities here. Hard to tell which is better: the Pillager or the Ransacker? Just remember that the Pillager boosts your orcs and is still available to play from the stack. Your orcs are already big enough to win without the Ransacker. If you’re shooting for the overwhelm, go for it. If you’re just trying to pile on wounds, check your other options.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Attacker. 3-9-2-5. When you play him from the stack (meaning a controlled site), you can add a burden for each controlled site.<br />
<br />
First off, realize that burdens don’t really do anything for besiegers. It’s initiative and threats that give the big payoffs (as we’ll see when I cover the support cards). Furthermore, he’s never going to be a mainstay of Sauron burdening decks either, because you have to add a whole site control element (and even then, the payoff is iffy). Besiegers are too combo intensive to waste space on this guy. Thumbs down.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Axeman. 3-9-2-5. Discard this guy in the skirmish phase to make a [S] minion strength +1 for each controlled site (+2 if you have the initiative).<br />
<br />
Hmmm. With other cards like the Pillager and Ransacker, this guy pales in comparison. You’d have to control at least 3 sites for him to be worthwhile. I’m really pretty certain that Besiegers generally won’t see the big payoff till late in the game. This guy just doesn’t seem worth waiting that long for. If initiative proves really easy to get, I may change my tune.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Engineer. 3-9-2-5. When you play him from the site stack, add 2 threats.<br />
<br />
Good threat addition. If you want to play with threats, this guy is a good idea. Another good utility minion.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Garrison. 3-9-2-5. Discard 2 cards from hand in the Regroup phase to stack a [S] orc.<br />
<br />
Vital to any besieger site-control strategy. The trick is getting him to survive till the Regroup phase. 9 and 2 aren’t really winning stats these days (all Aragorn has to do ishimmer him once with his sword). Still besides the very expensive Gorgoroth Troop, there aren’t any other options for stacking. You’ll just have to make him work.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Sapper. 3-9-2-5. Discard 2 cards from hand to play a [S] orc from the site stack in the shadow phase (only 1 card if the card played is a besieger).<br />
<br />
Another important utility minion. The Garrison stacks them, the Sapper plays them. Both these minions are vital for any site control strategy.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Soldier. 3-9-2-5. Response: if a besieger is about to take a wound, discard 2 cards from hand to prevent it.<br />
<br />
I don’t see the point of him yet. But it is true that most besiegers have only 2 vitality, and some have exertion abilities. This guy might be one way to help the Garrison survive till the regroup phase. His value really depends on how vital those besieger exertion abilities turn out to be.<br />
<br />
So there you have it. Besiegers are all about site control. I have no idea how effective this will be. These guys may turn out to be no better than Warg-riders: neat concept, lots of cool sounding abilities, but not a winner (or only viable in King block).<br />
Be that as it may, you have to make site control work if you want these guys to be a big part of your deck. Don’t forget those site control minions from Tower block either. It is also good to remember that 2 of the Besiegers, can be played independently from a Besieger strategy: Siege Commander and Gorgoroth Soldier. Siege Commander is just good, period. He’s a great throw in minion for other Sauron strategies and will do a lot of damage more often than not (and he’s got the advantage of a lower site #). Gorgoroth Soldier isn’t so impressive. But remember, he can at least ensure his own survival into the Regroup phase (and that can make the difference between your opponent stopping or double-moving).<br />
Personally, I’m more excited about the site 6 orcs listed above, but these guys might be worth a look. If you use them, I can’t imagine other Sauron orcs making a big appearance in the deck (it would dilute the site control strategy).<br />
<br />
OK, next we have a single possession to add to Vile Blade, Orc Scimitar, and Banner.<br />
<br />
Besieging Pike. 0 cost. Can go on any [S] orc and gives a strength +2. If you’ve got the initiative, it goes +3.<br />
<br />
Well, I’m not exactly throwing away my Vile Blades yet. I’m sure this works fine in a deck that focuses on getting the initiative. But personally, I’d rather use Vile Blade and add another element that boosts my minions (skirmishing Gondor or Elf comps).<br />
<br />
Note: By the way, that Banner from Towers block might have some interesting effects paired with the Besiegers. Something to consider.<br />
<br />
Next, we’ll look at the events. Not a lot of them.<br />
<br />
Siegecraft. 4 cost. If a [S] orc wins a skirmish, make all your [S] orcs fierce.<br />
<br />
Sauron has pretty good stats, so a win isn’t hard to arrange. The trick is going to be having 4 twilight available in the skirmish phase. Sauron costs a lot so you aren’t likely to have too many orcs out early in the game. It does no good to make your orcs fierce if it just gets them killed. That only encourages double-moving. Still, if you play it right, this could smack your opponent around a bit. Thumbs up.<br />
<br />
Anguish. 1 cost. Remove 3 Threats to make a character skirmishing a [S] orc strength -3.<br />
<br />
Not too bad. It’s the only pump event available besides Rope and Winch. In my opinion, it’s the better of the 2 even if it relies on you playing a threat strategy. It’s good to keep in mind that Sauron doesn’t get a lot of strength pumps. Enduring Evil and Eye of Barad-dur are the only others that come to mind. Notice that they are all pretty situational too. Enduring Evil relies on having burdens out, Anguish needs threats and Eye spots ring-bound companions.<br />
Besides being situational, Aguish also theoretically removes Threats just before you kill someone. So those are less Threats to trigger when the comp dies.<br />
Personally, I think you might be better using the texts of some of the minions above to boost your orcs rather than events. So I’m not too excited about this card. But it’s not too bad.<br />
<br />
Rope and Winch. 1 cost. Must spot 2 [S] orcs to play. You discard, they discard, you do the math . . . . whatever.<br />
<br />
I think every shadow culture got one of these cards. Makes my head hurt just looking at it. I don’t like it. But it actually might work well with initiative decks. I mean, suppose you got a couple of Orc Stalkers out and you play this event. Now, how many cards would you discard if you where the FP player? Tough choice ain’t it? Also remember that most good FP strategies up till now all stocked up on weapons and conditions that could play immediately from hand. This results in a FP player who has less cards in hand than the shadow player (usually).<br />
On a side note, this card helps you cycle your hand as well.<br />
Verdict: we got Anguish for Threat decks and R&W for Initiative decks. While I’m not wild about them, they’ve got real potential. Keep your eye on these cards in the future.<br />
<br />
Above the Battlement. 0 cost. Play a Besieger from the site stack or remove a burden to play a [S] orc from the discard pile.<br />
<br />
We all like recycling minions don’t we? This is pretty nice. Good way to get your Besiegers off your sites.<br />
Now, it’s important to note that this card is going to stink in King block if it isn’t in a Besieger strategy. Just tally up all the burdening cards in Sauron culture to see why. The Gorgoroth Attacker and Orc Officer aren’t going to hack it for ya. However, you combo this with Desperate Defense of the Ring and you got a nice recycling system.<br />
For Open and Standard format, it’s a great card.<br />
<br />
Din of Arms. 2 cost. Maneuver: If you got more Besiegers out than the twilight cost of the top card of someone else’s draw deck, you control a site and all Besiegers go strength +3.<br />
<br />
I have to say that I prefer Troop Tower as a site control mechanism. But it’s unique and vulnerable to condition removal. So you might want this card as a bit of back-up. Just seems unreliable to me. Better reserve judgment on this card until we know what kind of decks are being played out there (check to see what the average card cost in the deck is).<br />
<br />
Breached. 1 cost. Regroup: remove 4 Threats and spot 2 [S] orcs to force the FP player to put a companion on the dead pile.<br />
<br />
Ka-Boom! Cards like this always grab our attention don’t they? Let’s settle down and have a look.<br />
You need 4 Threats out (so this doesn’t work against a Frodo-Sam-Smeagol deck) and 2 of your Orcs have to survive to the Regroup phase. Getting orcs to survive shouldn’t be too tough (what else they got all that vitality for?).<br />
Note that this doesn’t work well with Besiegers since they aren’t really geared for Threat use. Besides, they typically only get 2 vitality so killing them is easier.<br />
Also consider that a couple uses of this card will likely render any other copies useless (since the fellowship may drop below 4 companions). But maybe we don’t care at that point anyway.<br />
I like it. It complements the overwhelm strategy really well. I don’t think it’s that useful in a wounding strategy since the FP player will probably just kill an exhausted comp. Which means this card only equals 1 wound in a Hate deck. Be careful in a burdening deck as well, because they might just ditch the companion with all the Desperate Defenses on him/her (you’d hate to lose those wouldn’t you?).<br />
Thumbs up.<br />
<br />
OK, next is the bread-and-butter of the red hordes. Conditions!<br />
<br />
Tower Walkway. 1 cost. Unique. Engine. Spot a [S] orc to play. All your Besiegers are strength +1 for each site you control. Regroup: Discard 3 [S] orcs and this condition to control a site.<br />
<br />
The big trouble with this condition is getting 3 orcs to survive till the regroup phase (remember that Besiegers only have 2 vitality). Discarding 3 of them also seems like a big price to pay since it almost begs the opponent to double-move on you. Once your site control kicks in, your opponent will be so far ahead of you it won’t make any difference.<br />
The only way to make the cost of -3 orcs hurt less, is to play cheap, high vitality orcs. But that means less slots for your Besiegers (the ones that make it all work).<br />
That said, 1 or 2 copies of this card might be a good idea for a Besieger deck. Just remember that the only good use you’re going to get out of it, is in the second regroup phase (after your opponent has double-moved) or some other situation where you’re sure there won’t be a double move (or you wish to encourage one).<br />
<br />
Troop Tower. 1 cost. Unique. Engine. Spot a [S] orc to play. All [S] orcs are strength +1 for each Besieger stacked on a site. Regroup: Discard a Besieger and this condition to control a site.<br />
<br />
Only works with Besiegers, but that’s no problem since I wouldn’t run site control with any other strategy. This is miles-away better than the Walkway. 1 orc is a much more affordable price to pay (and it’s easier to pull off too). At the least, you can get a Gorgoroth Soldier to survive easy enough. The big drawback is that this is unique (which is understandable since that strength bonus would really get out of hand otherwise). Just the same, I’d suggest playing all 4 copies of this since they discard themselves and there’s plenty of ways to cycle your hand.<br />
I’m going to stick my neck out and predict that this is going to become the most important card in the set for the Besieger strategy. Kinda like Hides for Dunland (but probably not quite so pivotal). You MUST control those sites to make the Besiegers work, and this is the best way to do it. Sure, you can toss in some Orc Fighters and they might help a lot. But that dilutes your Besieger strategy. Tower Walkway only works when they’re double-moving (ie. you’re losing) and Din of Arms is just plain unreliable. Nope, here’s your Hides Besieger players!<br />
<br />
Great Siege Towers. 1 cost. Engine. Play a Besieger, place a token here. In the skirmish phase remove a token to make a [S] orc strength +1 (limit +2).<br />
<br />
This is non-unique. But as I understand it, you can’t play 1 Besieger and place a token on all 4 copies (assuming you have all four out). They had this argument out on the message boards about the Berserker strategy. Nope, 1 Besieger = 1 token only.<br />
It’s an OK way to store up some strength for when you need it. But nothing spectacular. It’s certainly not going to be the foundation of your deck.<br />
Don’t even bother mixing this with other site 6 [S] orcs. They already have better strength boosting methods than this.<br />
<br />
Great Peril of Fire. 1 cost. To play, spot a Besieger or a site you control. Maneuver: Discard an Engine to discard a FP condition.<br />
<br />
This combos OK with Great Siege Towers. Once you add the text: discard to kill an FP condition, Great Siege Towers almost becomes a good card. I’ll state right now: there’s no way I’m ditching Troop Tower to remove a condition! I’d might ditch Tower Walkway, but I doubt I’ll use that card too much anyway.<br />
Verdict: it’s OK as a condition removal method for Besiegers. Any other [S] orcs are better off with Orc Patrol or Shadow’s Reach.<br />
<br />
Legions of Morgul. 3 cost. Spot 2 [S] orcs to play and add up to 3 Threats (yay!). Each time a comp is about to be killed, you may remove a Threat to make everyone fierce (hmm . . .). Regroup: discard this card and remove 3 Threats (Say What?!). <br />
<br />
What I said about the Mordor Guard I’ll say about this card: I’d prefer my Threats to stick around. If you want fierce orcs, use Siegecraft instead. Thumbs down.<br />
<br />
Stronghold of Cirith Ungol. 1 cost. Unique. Response: if [S] minion wins a skirmish, place a token here (limit of 1 per site). Regroup: add 2 twilight for each token here and discard.<br />
<br />
I used to think, what’s the point of adding twilight in the regroup phase? But then I got to thinking: all a shadow half really needs to do to be good is stop the other player from moving while you run ahead. If that’s all you want, this card really isn’t bad.<br />
There’s 2 things Sauron orcs are built for: 1) win the skirmish, and 2) survive (due to high vitality). This means that placing a token on this card will be rather easy and you’ll likely have some minions out by the regroup phase. Then you flood the pool with 4 or 6 twilight. Then just smile and dare them to move. I like it! If they stop, great! If they move, I’ve just added enough twilight to negate the cost disadvantage of Sauron. Either way, I win.<br />
The big drawback is that you can only do it once at each site on the site path. This unfortunately, limits you to using this perhaps twice in a game (3 if you’re lucky). I’d suggest using the card once you get 2 or 3 tokens on it. Don’t sit around waiting for Gandalf to nuke it. I’d wager that well timed use of this card has the potential to consistently stop your opponent once or twice every game (that’s about as often as current Nazgul players expect to stop their opponents).<br />
I think this card might be good paired up Fires Raged Unchecked or Encirclement (depending which orcs you’re using). After you overwhelm a couple comps, your opponent is probably going to be looking at your orcs rather suspiciously. With all the cost reduction cards out and the twilight pool flooded, chances are good that your opponents won’t risk a double move. Also, this helps you add Threats with Sauron’s Hatred.<br />
I’m excited about the possibilities with this card. Much better than Banner of the Eye since it doesn’t require site control. On the flip side, I’m thinking Banner is possibly a better card to pair with Besiegers for a similar effect. But even with Banners, I wouldn’t rule out including a few Strongholds.<br />
<br />
Fires Raged Unchecked. 1 cost. The site # of each [S] orc is -1 for each Threat. While you can spot 3 Threats, each [S] orc that isn’t roaming is strength +1.<br />
<br />
This isn’t unique. That means you can pile them up for bigger strength boosts. Combined with a Threat based strategy, this card can pay off big for little investment. I already mentioned its potential when teamed up with Stronghold.<br />
I’d strongly suggest this and Stronghold if you’re playing the site 6 orcs.<br />
<br />
Encirclement. 2 cost. Unique. For each 2 sites controlled, the twilight cost of each [S] orc is -1. Regroup: Spot a [S] minion to draw a card (or 2 if you spot a Besieger).<br />
<br />
Well, here’s the cost reduction card for the Besiegers. Pair it with Stronghold. Not bad, assuming the Besieger site control thing works in the first place.<br />
<br />
Sauron’s Hatred. 0 cost. To play, spot a [S] orc. Shadow: remove a Threat to play a [S] orc without the roaming penalty. Regroup: Spot a [S] orc and remove 4 twilight to add a Threat.<br />
<br />
This along with Fires Raged Unchecked go great in a Threat heavy strategy which ties in great with the site 6 Sauron orcs. Play a few copies to make sure it comes out early enough to make a difference.<br />
<br />
Some Secret Art of Flame. 1 cost. To play, spot a [S] orc. Regroup: play a [S] condition to place a token here. While you have 3 tokens here, you have the initiative, period.<br />
<br />
The only good method I’ve seen for Sauron to control the initiative (besides all the old discarding strategy stuff). Remember that this pays off big for all your Trackers and it triggers the Besieging Pike. Alas, initiative doesn’t do much for all your other site 6 Sauron orcs (except the Archer Troop). There are a couple of Besiegers that key off of Initiative, but it looks like the only real big payoffs are for your Trackers.<br />
However, I’d bet that the Trackers could be worked into either strategy (regular or besieger). If you’re running them, then a couple Flames is probably worthwhile.<br />
<br />
Rally the Host. 0 cost. Spot 2 [S] orcs to play. Regroup: exert 2 [S] orcs and remove a Threat to shuffle a [S] orc from play into your draw deck.<br />
<br />
Well . . . . that’s quirky . . . . Looks like their trying to give us something like Underdeeps for Sauron. But this doesn’t seem quite so good. Maybe a good card for the Sauron swarm maybe?<br />
The trouble with trying to judge cards like these is that it’s entirely possible that somebody’s going to find a killer combo for a card like this (tends to happen with deck manipulation cards). So I’m not going to give a verdict on this one. Feel free to experiment.<br />
<br />
THAT’S IT. ALL DONE! Boy, that took a long time (had to drag it out over 3 evenings)!<br />
<br />
So what are my overall impressions? Well . . . .<br />
1-Besiegers are a pretty dedicated strategy that won’t mix well with other strategies (even other Sauron strategies). I don’t care much for them personally . . . . too combo-intensive.<br />
2-Overwhelming is the big new thing for the site 6 Sauron orcs. Threats are also big for them. We’ll have to wait and see if this makes up for them not being damage +1.<br />
3-Initiative just made Desperate Defense of the Ring the new card to watch out for.<br />
4-Sauron is as condition-heavy as ever. Better pack a few Dead Marshes. In King block, you don’t have any ways to protect your stuff. But then again, FP condition removal is also pretty weak in King Block, if I’m not mistaken.<br />
5-It’s now easy to eliminate hand clog (and in doing so, control your drawing). This takes Sauron to a new level of flexibility: now you can choose whether you want a FP or Shadow hand for the next turn and you can tailor your shadow to fit all sizes of decks. This might just be enough to make Sauron seriously competitive.<br />
6-Site 6 Sauron Orcs might just become surprisingly good at slowing the opponent down. They might even prove more reliable than fierce Nazgul. Only time will tell.<br />
<br />
OK, hope I’ve given you enough ideas to start with. I don’t get a lot of opportunities to play-test, so I hope someone will take these ideas, test them, and then write about it.<br />
<br />
Right! I’m going to bed.<br />
